1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
6 Minute English from bbclearningenglish.com

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBC Learning English. I'm Pippa.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:11,000
And I'm Neil.

4
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Now, Neil, have you ever wanted to be a musician?

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Oh yes, Pippa. I still want to be a musician. I've been playing my guitar since I was 14.

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,000
Wow. Well, maybe one day you'll manage it.

7
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Who knows? What about you?

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,000
I don't think I'd like to be a musician. I think it would be a bit stressful,

9
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,000
especially if you had lots of fans and were really successful.

10
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Yeah, I wonder what life as a musician is actually like.

11
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:42,000
We'll be finding that out in this programme as we hear from some people around the UK

12
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
who would like to become successful musicians and will even listen to some of their music too.

13
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:51,000
But first, I have a question for you, Neil.

14
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:56,000
In the UK, we have a weekly chart of the best-selling songs in the country

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,000
and the top-selling song is called the number one.

16
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:05,000
But which musical artist do you think has had the most UK number one songs?

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Is it A. The Beatles, B. Ed Sheeran or C. Elvis Presley?

18
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Oh, well, I think that's easy. It must be surely The Beatles.

19
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Well, I'll reveal the answer at the end of the programme.

20
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Now, getting a number one song is a dream for many musicians,

21
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
but if you want to become a musician, where do you start?

22
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:32,000
I grew up in a really rich music scene in St Ives.

23
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
I was going to open mics from the age of about eleven.

24
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:41,000
This is Bailey. She lives in St Ives in Cornwall on the south-west coast of England.

25
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
She says she was going to open mic nights from a young age.

26
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:49,000
And mic nights are events where anyone can sing or play music.

27
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Bailey talked about her life as a musician to BBC Learning English programme,

28
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:55,000
My Song, My Home.

29
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
I would go to these songwriter's circles at the Kettle and Wink

30
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
on, like, a Friday night after school,

31
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
where I'd be like the youngest person by, like, fifty years,

32
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,000
but I'd sit in a circle of a bunch of old men

33
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:12,000
and they'd play James Taylor and Carol King and the Eagles

34
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
and lots of 70s music and I guess that's influenced me massively.

35
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
But I guess, you know, everyone kind of took me under the wing growing up.

36
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
When she was younger, Bailey went to songwriter's circles.

37
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,000
These are meetings for people interested in writing their own music.

38
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Bailey remembers sitting with a bunch of old men.

39
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
A bunch is an informal way to talk about a group of people.

40
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
The older men in the group would play music from the 1970s

41
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
and Bailey says they took her under their wing.

42
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,000
If you take somebody under your wing, you decide to protect them or guide them.

43
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Let's meet another musician, Josh.

44
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:56,000
So I learnt my first proper song on guitar when I was about thirteen.

45
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,000
I literally started busking the moment I could kind of do that.

46
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Josh lives in London and is a busker.

47
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
This means that he performs on the street or in public places to earn money.

48
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Busking is a common way for musicians to make money and perform to more people.

49
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
And as Josh told BBC Learning English programme My Song, My Home,

50
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,000
it can help musicians to get new opportunities.

51
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:25,000
It's been kind of like my main earner that's kept me going for the last ten or so years.

52
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
From that it's then got me various different opportunities.

53
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:34,000
It's got me all my gigs, got me all my connections, so I owe a lot to busking.

54
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Busking is Josh's main earner. It's his main source of money.

55
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:42,000
He says that busking has got him all his gigs and connections.

56
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Gigs are musical concerts and it's an informal slang word.

57
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Josh says he owes a lot to busking.

58
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:56,000
If you owe a lot to someone or something, you have success or happiness because of that personal thing.

59
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:00,000
So would you like to listen to some of Josh's music, Neil?

60
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Of course I would.

61
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Well, here's a bit of his song That Side of the Wall,

62
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:08,000
which he performed for BBC Learning English programme My Song, My Home.

63
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Wow, Josh is pretty good, isn't he? I'd love to hear more.

64
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Well, you can find performances by the musicians in the series on our website, bbclanningenglish.com,

65
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
and we'll also put a link in the notes below this episode.

66
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,000
OK, so what about your question, Pippa?

67
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Yes, I asked which artist had the most number one songs in the UK,

68
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
OK, so what about your question, Pippa?

69
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Yes, I asked which artist had the most number one songs in the UK charts,

70
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:06,000
The Beatles, Ed Sheeran or Elvis Presley, and you said The Beatles, Neil.

71
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
But the answer is actually Elvis Presley.

72
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:14,000
He's had 21 number one songs and The Beatles have had 18.

73
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Really? Well, that's OK. I love The King as well.

74
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:21,000
OK, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this musical episode.

75
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,000
Starting with open mic nights, events where anyone can sing or play music.

76
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:32,000
Songwriter circles are meetings for people interested in writing their own music.

77
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
A bunch of people is a group of people.

78
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:39,000
The expression take someone under your wing means to protect or guide someone.

79
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
Busking is performing in a public place for money,

80
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
and a busker is someone who performs on the street for money.

81
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Your main earner is your main source of income.

82
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Gigs are musical concerts.

83
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,000
And the expression to owe a lot to someone or something

84
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
means to have success or happiness because of that personal thing.

85
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Once again, our six minutes are up,

86
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:07,000
but you can find My Song, My Home on our website, bbclearningenglish.com.

87
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:11,000
Watch the songs and sing along and learn more about the vocabulary in the lyrics.

88
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:16,000
We'll see you again soon for some more trending topics and useful vocabulary.

89
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Bye for now.

90
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Goodbye.

91
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:24,000
Six Minute English from bbclearningenglish.com

